<body>
    <%- include('partials/header') %>

        <main>
            <div class="hero">
                <h1>Analyzing Early Economic and Financial Indicators for Recession in the U.S</h1>
                <p>Group ID: 5</p>
                <p>Members: May Sabai, Emily Lu</p>
            </div>

            <section id="project-summary">
                <h2>Project Summary</h2>
                <p>
                    Recessions are typically only identified after they have already caused widespread economic damage.
                    This project aims to detect early warning signs of U.S. recessions by analyzing key economic and
                    financial indicators (like Unemployment, Inflation, S&P 500, and VIX) from 1968 to 2026.
                </p>
                <p>
                    To study how these indicators behaved in the months leading up to past recessions, we use
                    exploratory data analysis and quantitative modeling to find recurring patterns. The ultimate goal is
                    to determine if current economic conditions resemble historical pre-recession environments,
                    providing earlier and clearer signals for the future.
                </p>
            </section>

            <div class="content-grid">
                <section id="broader-impacts">
                    <h2>Broader Impacts</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Public Awareness:</strong> Helps everyday people understand economic warning signs
                            to make informed financial decisions.</li>
                        <li><strong>Personal Finance:</strong> Encourages proactive behaviors like building emergency
                            savings and managing debt responsibly before a downturn.</li>
                        <li><strong>Business Strategy:</strong> Allows small businesses to adjust hiring, inventory, and
                            investments ahead of economic shifts.</li>
                        <li><strong>Risk Management:</strong> Provides investors and financial institutions with clearer
                            signals for portfolio allocation.</li>
                        <li><strong>Policy Responses:</strong> Helps policymakers identify reliable early indicators for
                            more timely and targeted economic interventions.</li>
                    </ul>
                </section>

                <section id="data-sources">
                    <h2>Data Sources</h2>
                    <ol>
                        <li>U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics, <a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/UNRATE"
                                target="_blank" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">Unemployment
                                Rate</a> [UNRATE], retrieved from FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis, February 4,
                            2026.</li>
                        <li>World Bank, <a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/FPCPITOTLZGUSA" target="_blank"
                                style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">Inflation, consumer prices for the
                                United States</a> [FPCPITOTLZGUSA], retrieved from FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St.
                            Louis, February 4, 2026.</li>
                        <li>Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System, <a
                                href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/FEDFUNDS" target="_blank"
                                style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">Federal Funds Effective Rate</a>
                            [FEDFUNDS], retrieved from FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis.</li>
                        <li>U.S. Energy Information Administration, <a
                                href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/DCOILWTICO" target="_blank"
                                style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">Crude Oil Prices: West Texas
                                Intermediate (WTI)</a> [DCOILWTICO], retrieved from FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of
                            St. Louis.</li>
                        <li>Yahoo Finance, <a href="https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/%5ESPX/history/" target="_blank"
                                style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">S&P 500 Index Historical Data</a>
                            [^SPX], retrieved from Yahoo Finance.</li>
                        <li>Yahoo Finance, <a href="https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/%5EVIX/" target="_blank"
                                style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">CBOE Volatility Index (^VIX)
                                Historical Data</a> [^VIX], retrieved from Yahoo Finance.</li>
                        <li>Yahoo Finance, <a href="https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/GOLD/" target="_blank"
                                style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">Gold Historical Data</a>
                            [GOLD], retrieved from Yahoo Finance.</li>
                        <li>Recession, <a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/USREC" target="_blank"
                                style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">Recession indicator</a>
                            [USREC], retrieved from FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis.</li>
                    </ol>
                </section>
            </div>

            <section id="historical-recessions">
                <h2>8 US Economic Recessions</h2>
                <p>This project analyzes eight major U.S. recessions, each driven by unique economic triggers:</p>
                <table class="table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Recession</th>
                            <th>Primary Cause</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1969 Vietnam/Fed Tightening</strong></td>
                            <td>Post-war spending + aggressive Fed rate hikes to control inflation</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1973 Oil Embargo Stagflation</strong></td>
                            <td>OPEC oil embargo caused energy crisis and stagflation</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1980 Volcker Inflation Fight</strong></td>
                            <td>Paul Volcker's Fed sharply raised rates to break the inflation cycle</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1981 High Interest Rates</strong></td>
                            <td>Continuation of Volcker policy; deepest post-WWII unemployment at the time</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1990 Gulf War Oil Shock</strong></td>
                            <td>Gulf War oil shock combined with the savings and loan crisis</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>2001 Dot-Com Bust</strong></td>
                            <td>Collapse of overvalued tech sector, stock market crash, 9/11</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>2008 Great Recession</strong></td>
                            <td>Housing bubble collapse, banking system failure, credit freeze</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>2020 COVID Pandemic</strong></td>
                            <td>Sudden global pandemic-driven economic shutdown</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </section>

            <section id="analysis">
                <h2>Analysis</h2>
                <a href="/eda#avg-trajectory" style="text-decoration: none; color: inherit;">
                    <ul>
                        <li>The S&P 500 often declines 3 to 6 months before recession.</li>
                        <li>VIX tends to increase sharply near recession onset.</li>
                        <li>Inflation and interest rate patterns vary across economic periods.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <div class="content-grid">
                        <figure>
                            <img src="images/EDA/average%20line%20graph%20economic%20indicator.png"
                                alt="Average line graph economic indicator">
                        </figure>
                        <figure>
                            <img src="images/EDA/average%20line%20graph%20financial%20indicator.png"
                                alt="Average line graph financial indicator">
                        </figure>
                    </div>
