            </section>

            <section id="machine-learning">
                <h2>Machine Learning</h2>
                <p>[Brief overview of ML approach]</p>
            </section>

            <section id="major-findings">
                <h2>Major Findings</h2>
                <p>
                    In compare current economic data (2024 - 2026) to past pre-recession periods,we have used two
                    methods: Spearman correlation and Dynamic Time Warping (DTW).
                </p>
                <table class="table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th></th>
                            <th>Spearman</th>
                            <th>Dynamic Time Wraping (DTW)</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Measurement focus</td>
                            <td>Directional alignment of trends at each point in time</td>
                            <td>Overall similarity in the shape of trends over time</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Score interpretation</td>
                            <td>Higher values indicate stronger synchronization in movement</td>
                            <td>Higher values indicate stronger similarity in pattern, regardless of timing</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Analytical insight</td>
                            <td>Assesses whether current conditions are evolving in line with past periods</td>
                            <td>Assesses whether current dynamics structurally resemble past cycles</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>

                <a href="/major-findings#overall-ranking" style="text-decoration: none; color: inherit;">
                    <p>The two bar graphs below rank all eight recessions by their average similarity score across all
                        <strong>six indicators</strong> and all <strong>six time windows</strong>.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/Overall-Recession-similarity.png"
                            alt="Overall Recession Similarity Ranking">
                    </figure>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>2008</strong> is the clearest match to today, with the highest similarity in both
                            measures, followed by <strong>2020</strong> as the second closest.</li>
                        <li>Most other recessions show only moderate similarity (scores mostly between 40–59), meaning
                            today's conditions are not strongly aligned with them.</li>
                        <li>DTW scores are consistently higher than Spearman, suggesting the overall patterns/trends
                            look
                            similar, even if the exact relationships between indicators are weaker.</li>
                    </ul>
                </a>
            </section>

        </main>

